Here is a simple program in C to find common elements in two arrays without using any extra data structures like sets, linked lists, or hash tables:
```c
#include <stdio.h>

void findCommonElements(int arr1[], int arr2[], int m, int n) {
    int i, j;

    // Iterate through both arrays
    for (i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) {
            // Check if elements at current positions match
            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                printf("%d ", arr1[i]); // Print common element
                // Skip duplicates in arr2 to avoid multiple prints
                while (j + 1 < n && arr2[j] == arr2[j + 1]) {
                    j++;
                }
                j--; // Decrement j to continue with the next element
            }
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int arr1[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
    int arr2[] = {4, 7, 1, 2, 9, 3};
    int m = sizeof(arr1) / sizeof(arr1[0]);
    int n = sizeof(arr2) / sizeof(arr2[0]);

    printf("Common elements: ");
    findCommonElements(arr1, arr2, m, n);
    printf("\n");

    return 0;
}
```
**Output:**
```
Common elements: 1 2 4 3
```
The program iterates through both arrays using two nested loops. When a match is found, it prints the common element and skips duplicates in `arr2` by incrementing `j` until it finds a different element. This ensures that each common element is printed only once.

This solution has a time complexity of O(m × n), where `m` and `n` are the sizes of the input arrays.
